\begin_layout Title
Blank
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring.
 A 
\series bold
seminorm 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (or an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset


\series bold
-seminorm
\series default
)
\series bold
 
\series default
is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|\colon A\to\mathbb{R}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

 is either the zero map (in which case we call 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
zero seminorm
\series default
) or is a nonzero map which satisfies the following properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\|0\|=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|1\|=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|a\|=\|-a\|
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have the 
\series bold
triangle inequality
\series default
, which says
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|a+b\|\leq\|a\|+\|b\|
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 satisfies the 
\series bold
strong triangle inequality
\series default
, which says
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|a+b\|\leq\max\{\|a\|,\|b\|\}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
non-archimedean
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is 
\series bold
submultiplicative
\series default
, which says
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\|ab\|\leq\|a\|\|b\|\label{eq:inequalityjlk}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

.
 If the inequality 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:inequalityjlk})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is an equality, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
multiplicative
\series default
.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
power-multiplicative 
\series default
if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|a^{n}\|=\|a\|^{n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\|\cdot\|)$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
seminormed ring
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In order to simplify our notation in what follows, we often refer to the
 pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\|\cdot\|)$
\end_inset

 via its underlying commutative ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, where we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as a commutative ring which is equipped with a seminorm 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|\colon A\to\mathbb{R}_{\geq0}$
\end_inset

, giving it the structure of a seminormed ring.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 satisfies a property (such as being a norm), then we also say A satisfies
 that property (such as being a normed ring).
 If we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a seminormed ring
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then it is understood that the seminorm of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|_{A}$
\end_inset

 or even more simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 if context is clear.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A=(A,\|\cdot\|)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'=(A,\|\cdot\|')$
\end_inset

 are two seminormed rings which share the underlying commuative ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 as seminormed rings if and only if the identity map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{id}\colon A\to A$
\end_inset

 is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be seminormed rings.
 A map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
morphism of seminormed rings 
\series default
if it is a ring homomorphism which is 
\series bold
bounded 
\series default
meaning there exists a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\varphi(a)\|\leq C\|a\|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 The smallest such 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\varphi\|$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
contractive 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\varphi\|\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
isometry 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\varphi(a)\|=\|a\|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

There are two categories to consider: first we have the category of all
 seminormed rings as objects and bounded morphisms as morphisms.
 This category is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{SnRing}^{\mathrm{bdd}}$
\end_inset

.
 Next we have the category of all seminormed rings as objects and isometries
 as morphisms.
 This category is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{SnRing}^{\mathrm{isom}}$
\end_inset

.
 Unless otherwise specified, we will always work in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{SnRing}^{\mathrm{bdd}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $A=(A,\|\cdot\|)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'=(A,\|\cdot\|')$
\end_inset

 are two seminormed rings which share the underlying commuative ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then the identity map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{id}\colon A\to A$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism if and only if there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{-1}\|a\|\leq\|a\|'\leq C\|a\|
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, by which we mean an isomorphism in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{SnRing}^{\mathrm{bdd}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a seminormed ring and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $uv=1$
\end_inset

).
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\|1\|=\|uv\|\leq\|u\|\|v\|$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
From 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-seminorms to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-filtrations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unless otherwise specified, we fix 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 (for instance take 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=1/2$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-seminorm such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|a\|\leq1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 (in particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is non-archimedean).
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{n}=\{a\in A\mid\|a\|\leq\varepsilon^{n}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-filtration, called the 
\series bold
filtration induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that we obviously have 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}=A$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{n})$
\end_inset

 is obviously a descending sequence of sets.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in A_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|ab\|\leq\|a\|\|b\|\leq\varepsilon^{m+n}.
\]

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in A_{m+n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{m}A_{n}\subseteq A_{m+n}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal.
 It is clearly closed under scalar multiplication since 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}A_{n}\subseteq A_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that it is closed under addition, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|a+b\|\leq\max\{\|a\|,\|b\|\}\leq\varepsilon^{n}.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is closed under addition as well, so it is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
From 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-filtrations to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-seminorms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=(A_{n})$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-filtration.
 Define an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-seminorm 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|\cdot\|=\begin{cases}
\varepsilon^{n} & \text{if }a\in A_{n}\backslash A_{n+1}\\
0 & \text{if }a\in\bigcap_{n\in\mathbb{N}}A_{n}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-seminorm, called the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset


\series bold
-seminorm induced by the filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{n})$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\end_layout

